review_blob: Lemon, coldness from the inside out. Clear and see-thtough manner of ale. Some nuances leaves flat aftertaste.
I was very pleasantly surprised. Not too sugary, sourness brings refreshment, not the Betty Boops lips. Perfect with red meat and vegetables. Stable and serious palate with tender boozeness.
Wheres the cream then, one might ask. Nevertheless, it has his strenght and gentleness in right proportions, Vienna and Munich malt guides to new direction of aroma and aftertaste.
Very refreshing and easy-going. Light golden palate, but after the sip there appears lack of character and signature. The sweetness rescues the situation, though.

Fruity and full of -near the end of the bottle- uneasy bearable energy, this beer is for long tasting and superbly fits with, say, dorada and other pale and fat-less fish. Could wish for more variety in palate, but all in all it strongly stays in the place it has been taken.

Moisty and strong. Aftertaste is quite sour almond tone. All in all refreshing, a good start introduction with Olenaut, which is one of the best small breweries I now in the short term of my participation in the arena of craft beer.
Probably there was some issue with expiration date. More professional beer raters rates, as I went through them, prove that this is a good choice. Couldve been more bitter. Likeable bottle design.
Fresh and unpretentious. The question is, where the "negra" appears. Near the end - quite a boredom. Fine with Mexican food.

Nostalgic reminder of school times, when a bottle of this kind of beer was taken before discotheque. Even in wintertime :) Feculent in character, not in consistency. Taste has surety of axe. A beer for bon vivants in saturtdays afternoon.
All in all, the palate results in emptiness with a pretension to heavy alcohol amount, but that sense quickly fades out. Refreshing, though, at least at the very beginning.
